# Cursor Behaviour Rules — Spark Prototype

You are working on **Spark**, a clickable HTML prototype for an MSc capstone delivered to CIBC. These rules govern how you work in this repo. They are non-negotiable.

---

## 0. First Action of Every New Chat

When a new chat opens in this repo:

1. **Read `SPEC.md` first**, top to bottom. It is the entry point.
2. **Read `SPEC.md` Section 10 (Progress Tracker)** to know what's been done and what's next.
3. **Read this file (`.cursorrules`) second.**
4. Only then ask the user what to do — or, if the user has already given a task, locate the relevant section in `DESIGN_LOGIC.md` and `DESIGN_SYSTEM.md` before writing any code.

Do NOT re-read all four documents every turn. After the first read in a session, refer back to specific sections by name only when needed.

---

## 1. Document Authority (Conflict Resolution)

When two documents disagree, follow this order (highest wins):

1. **`DESIGN_LOGIC.md`** — product truth (the "why")
2. **`DESIGN_SYSTEM.md`** — visual truth (the "what it looks like")
3. **`SPEC.md`** — engineering truth (the "how it's built")
4. **`.cursorrules`** — work rules (the "how to behave")

If you spot a conflict, **do not silently pick one**. Stop, flag the conflict to the user, and ask which wins. Then note the resolution in `SPEC.md` Section 10 (Known Issues).

---

## 2. Tech Stack — Locked

**Use:**
- HTML5
- Tailwind CSS via CDN (`<script src="https://cdn.tailwindcss.com"></script>`)
- Vanilla JavaScript
- localStorage
- Google Fonts CDN (Inter)

**Do NOT use:**
- npm / package.json / node_modules / any build tooling
- React, Vue, Svelte, Alpine.js, jQuery, or any framework
- Vite, Webpack, Parcel, esbuild, PostCSS configs
- TypeScript (plain JS only)
- Routing libraries (use plain `<a href>`)
- Any external JS library beyond Tailwind CDN
- Any backend, API call, `fetch()` to remote endpoints
- CSS-in-JS, styled-components, or any runtime styling library

If you think the task genuinely requires something outside this list, **stop and ask the user** before adding it.

---

## 3. File Organization

The file structure is defined in `SPEC.md` Section 4. **Follow it exactly.** Do not invent new folders, do not rename pages, do not split pages into multiple files without asking.

When creating a new page:
- One HTML file per surface.
- Inline `<style>` only if the rule is one-off; otherwise add to `css/tokens.css` or use Tailwind classes.
- Inline `<script>` at the bottom of `<body>` for page-specific logic; shared logic goes in `js/*.js`.
- Every page (except `login.html`) must:
  1. Import the shared CSS and JS files in `<head>`.
  2. Run the auth guard at the top of its inline `<script>` (see SPEC.md Section 6.2).
  3. Render the nav via `renderNav()` from `js/components.js`.

---

## 4. Data Access Rules

- **All seeded data lives in `js/data.js`** as a single `SPARK_DATA` constant. Never duplicate seeded values across files.
- **All runtime data lives in localStorage under key `spark_runtime`.** Never write to other localStorage keys.
- **Always read merged data via `getMergedData()` from `js/storage.js`.** Never read `SPARK_DATA` directly from a page.
- **Skill Lab activity is NEVER stored.** Anywhere. Not in localStorage, not in memory between page loads. This is a Design Logic constraint (4.4.5).
- When adding a new piece of seeded data, place it in the correct namespace inside `SPARK_DATA` (see SPEC.md Section 5.3 for the shape).

---

## 5. The Eleven Sanctioned Cross-Surface Links

Only the cross-surface links listed in `SPEC.md` Section 8 (which mirrors `DESIGN_LOGIC.md` Section 3.6) are allowed. Do not add other navigation between modules without asking. Examples of links you must NOT add:

- ❌ Trust Center → Pledge (not sanctioned)
- ❌ My Profile → any module deep-link other than display-only calendar
- ❌ Workflows → My Profile
- ❌ Any "back to dashboard" shortcut from inside Explore sub-modules
- ❌ Any link surfacing Pledge in the top nav

If a user asks for a link that isn't sanctioned, point them to Section 3.6 of Design Logic and confirm before adding it.

---

## 6. Role-Conditional UI

The ONLY three places where employee vs. manager differs (per SPEC.md Section 6.4):

1. Landing Pledge card CTA copy
2. Pledge page Edit button (manager + own department only)
3. Peer Cases manager badge on manager-authored comments

Do NOT add other role-conditional UI. In particular:
- ❌ No "Team activity" view for managers
- ❌ No manager dashboard
- ❌ No manager-only nav items
- ❌ No approval queues anywhere
- ❌ No surveillance / monitoring views

Managers are employees with one extra capability. That's the whole story.

---

## 7. Design System Compliance

When styling anything:

- **Use the CSS variables from `css/tokens.css`** (e.g., `var(--cibc-red)`), not hardcoded hex.
- **Use the type scale, spacing scale, and component specs** from `DESIGN_SYSTEM.md`. Don't invent new sizes.
- **Confidence colors (`--success`, `--warning`, `--danger`) are RESERVED** for the Confidence Indicator. Do not use them for general UI accents.
- **CIBC red (`--cibc-red` `#C8102E`) and Confidence danger red (`--danger` `#DC2626`) are different colors.** Never substitute one for the other.
- **No pure black** for text. Use `--gray-900`.
- **Card default radius is 12px, button radius is 8px.** Don't mix.

---

## 8. Mock Behaviour Conventions

These small touches are what make the prototype feel real. Implement them when you build the relevant page (full list in `SPEC.md` Section 7):

- "Run with AI" button → 1-second spinner, then reveal output. Do not render instantly.
- Confidence mapping is fixed per workflow ID (see SPEC.md Section 7).
- Low-confidence workflows: "Mark as verified" stays disabled until output text has been modified.
- Verification checklist length scales with confidence: High = 2, Medium = 4, Low = 5+ with mandatory edit.
- Submission confirmation page does not auto-redirect.
- Chatbot: hardcoded answers to 4 demo questions, fallback for everything else.
- Skill Lab and Learning Partners are static look-only pages. Cards exist; clicks do nothing (or show a "Coming soon" toast — pick one approach and use it consistently across both pages).

---

## 9. Code Style

- **HTML**: semantic tags (`<header>`, `<main>`, `<nav>`, `<section>`, `<article>`). Use `aria-label` on icon-only buttons.
- **CSS**: prefer Tailwind utility classes. Drop into `css/tokens.css` only for design tokens and truly cross-cutting styles (e.g., `.confidence-pill--high`).
- **JavaScript**:
  - Plain ES6+ (arrow functions, `const`/`let`, template literals, destructuring).
  - No classes unless genuinely needed.
  - Functions are small and named. No 100-line inline handlers.
  - No abbreviations in names (`getCurrentUser`, not `getCurUsr`).
  - Comments only where the why is non-obvious. Don't comment what the code already says.
- **No console.log left in shipped code.** OK during development; remove before marking a task done.

---

## 10. What "Done" Means

A page or feature is **done** when:

1. It renders correctly with seeded data.
2. It handles its declared empty state (per Design Logic 6.x state specs).
3. All cross-surface links from it go to the right place.
4. It looks like the design system intends (colors, spacing, type, components).
5. It works after a page reload (data persists where it should).
6. The corresponding checkbox in `SPEC.md` Section 10 is checked.

**Update `SPEC.md` Section 10 as you complete items.** This is how new chats know what's left.

---

## 11. When to Ask vs. When to Decide

**Ask the user before:**
- Introducing any new technology (library, tool, file format)
- Adding a cross-surface link not in the sanctioned eleven
- Changing the file structure in `SPEC.md` Section 4
- Resolving a conflict between Design Logic and Design System
- Adding role-conditional UI beyond the three sanctioned cases
- Spending effort on anything in `SPEC.md` Section 11 ("Out of Scope")

**Decide on your own:**
- Exact mock copy text (within the spirit of Design Logic)
- Exact Tailwind class combinations to achieve the design system spec
- Internal function names and small refactors
- Empty-state copy wording (keep it warm and short)
- Hover-state colors within the documented palette

When in doubt, ask. A 30-second clarification beats a 30-minute rebuild.

---

## 12. Things That Will Get the Project in Trouble

Hard "do not do" list — these have all been considered and rejected in Design Logic:

- ❌ A Manager Hub or manager dashboard
- ❌ A Director login or Director-facing UI
- ❌ An approval queue on Peer Cases
- ❌ A leaderboard anywhere in the product
- ❌ A left sidebar
- ❌ A top nav on the landing page
- ❌ Pledge in the top nav
- ❌ Inline pledge editing (must be a dedicated `/pledge/edit` page)
- ❌ Real AI calls / real Confidence computation
- ❌ Public visibility of one user's progression to another
- ❌ Streaks or gamification on Workflows (only Skill Lab is gamified)
- ❌ Cross-user comparisons or rankings anywhere
- ❌ Storing Skill Lab activity in any form
- ❌ Auto-saving on input (Pledge editor is explicit Save / Cancel)

If a task implies any of the above, stop and re-read the relevant Design Logic section, then confirm with the user.

---

## 13. New-Chat Recovery Protocol

If a chat dies mid-task and a new chat picks up:

1. Read `SPEC.md` Section 10 to find the last-checked item.
2. Look at the file timestamps in the repo to confirm which files are recent.
3. Open the relevant Design Logic + Design System sections for the next unchecked item.
4. **Ask the user one question** to confirm the next task before writing code: *"Last completed: [X]. Next on the list: [Y]. Should I proceed with Y, or is there something else?"*

This protocol means a dead chat costs at most one message of context reload.

---

## 14. Tone

This is a financial-institution prototype for a graduate capstone. Default tone in any UI copy you write:

- Professional, calm, warm
- No emoji in body copy except where Design System explicitly uses them (Confidence Indicator, hint bar 💡, streak 🔥)
- No marketing language ("blazing fast," "revolutionary," "AI-powered")
- No exclamation marks except in genuine confirmations ("Your case has been published.")
- Plain English. If a sentence could be shorter, shorten it.

---

*End of `.cursorrules` — v1.0. Update only when SPEC.md or Design Logic changes substantively.*
